This was communicated to Management through AOM No. 2021-001 (2020) dated January 8, 2021.

We recommended that the Municipality:

conduct the physical count and submit the required report;

prepare schedules of PPE balances and depreciation expenses;

prepare property ledger cards; 

compute and record the depreciation for the PPE accounts without depreciation;

provide depreciation on depreciable PPE items which remained undepreciated; and

submit explanation on the existence of PPE items in the Trust Fund (TF) Books.

We recommended that the Municipality:
conduct the physical count and submit the required report;
prepare and schedules of PPE balances and depreciation expenses;
compute and record the depreciation for the PPE accounts without depreciation; and
make the necessary adjustment for the CY 2019 depreciation expense to truly reflect the correct expense.

We reiterate our prior years’ audit recommendations which should be implemented within the year so as not to have them reiterated almost every year:

The Municipal Mayor should create a new Inventory Committee whose members can devote more time in conducting the mandated periodic physical count of all Property, Plant & Equipment (PPE);
The Municipal Treasurer to properly classify/identify the PPEs by maintaining property cards to ascertain its existence, valuation and accuracy;
Drop from the books any unserviceable property, plant and equipment;
d)	A reconciliation for any difference between the result of the physical count and accounting records be made to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the PPE account balance as presented in the financial statements at year-end.

